WEBVTT

00:01.602 --> 00:09.690
♪♪

00:09.690 --> 00:17.818
♪♪

00:17.818 --> 00:25.906
♪♪

00:32.272 --> 00:36.677
‐Not everything has
a beginning, sweetheart.

00:36.677 --> 00:38.118
You can move somewhere
you ain't been,

00:38.118 --> 00:40.761
but what's that mean?

00:40.761 --> 00:44.444
You ain't where you was.

00:44.444 --> 00:47.968
You ain't where you gonna be.

00:47.968 --> 00:49.850
That don't ever change.

00:53.974 --> 00:58.979
'Round and 'round and 'round,
doing circles 'round the sun.

00:58.979 --> 01:03.343
Everything new

01:03.343 --> 01:05.746
and old

01:05.746 --> 01:07.588
and always.

01:07.588 --> 01:11.151
♪♪

01:22.122 --> 01:26.446
‐Initial descent,
alpha at 18.5 degrees,

01:26.446 --> 01:30.450
heat shield at 1,900 Celsius,
all systems go.

01:30.450 --> 01:33.213
Trajectory?
‐Trajectory nominal.

01:33.213 --> 01:35.816
‐Vibration alert.
Attitude alert ‐‐

01:35.816 --> 01:37.217
alpha.
‐Angle of attack?

01:37.217 --> 01:40.020
‐Alpha at 18.1 and decreasing.

01:40.020 --> 01:42.382
Alpha dot is
negative one degree per second.

01:42.382 --> 01:44.144
Shield at 2,100.

01:44.144 --> 01:46.507
‐Auto‐correct not active.
‐Auto‐correct initiate.

01:46.507 --> 01:48.028
‐Auto‐correct not responding.

01:48.028 --> 01:49.590
‐Permission for manual override.

01:49.590 --> 01:51.271
‐Permission granted.

01:51.271 --> 01:55.716
‐Go manual. All right.

01:55.716 --> 01:58.198
‐Shield at 2,100.

01:58.198 --> 02:02.202
Shield at 2,200.
‐Come on.

02:02.202 --> 02:04.444
‐2,300.

02:04.444 --> 02:05.646
2,400.

02:05.646 --> 02:07.568
‐Heat limit.

02:07.568 --> 02:09.810
Heat limit.

02:09.890 --> 02:12.132
Heat limit.

02:12.132 --> 02:14.054
Heat limit.
‐What the fuck?!

02:14.054 --> 02:15.455
‐Heat limit.

02:15.455 --> 02:17.217
‐What's going on in there?
‐Heat limit.

02:17.217 --> 02:20.901
‐Goddamn cicada.
‐Limit exceeded.

02:20.901 --> 02:23.223
‐I got it. I got it.
‐Limit exceeded.

02:23.223 --> 02:25.345
Limit exceeded.
‐Ohh.

02:25.345 --> 02:30.350
‐Zed's dead, baby.
‐Let's shut it down.

02:30.350 --> 02:34.755
[ Motor powers down ]

02:34.755 --> 02:37.157
Okay, everybody
come on out of there.

02:39.560 --> 02:43.243
Uh, get it sprayed, checked,
do whatever you have to do.

02:43.243 --> 02:44.897
‐Take a couple hours.

02:46.967 --> 02:51.451
‐Everybody, let's take a break
till he's got it reset.

02:51.451 --> 02:53.974
Kayla, we should go ahead
and do that now.

02:53.974 --> 02:55.736
‐Yep. Yep.

02:57.057 --> 02:59.499
Can I get a paper towel, please?

02:59.499 --> 03:03.303
‐We need Aiko
for her systems expertise

03:03.303 --> 03:06.306
and Matteo for medical.

03:06.306 --> 03:08.829
So it really comes down
to these two.

03:08.829 --> 03:11.431
Fletcher has mission experience.
He's a good pilot.

03:11.431 --> 03:13.714
But now that we have
both me and Tom,

03:13.714 --> 03:15.235
there's some redundancy.

03:15.235 --> 03:17.998
Hewitt has never been to space.

03:17.998 --> 03:20.440
But cutting our science
specialist would impact

03:20.440 --> 03:22.362
our work on the surface.

03:22.362 --> 03:26.887
It's a difficult choice,
but I suggest cutting Fletcher.

03:30.410 --> 03:32.452
‐Doesn't keeping the more
experienced astronaut

03:32.452 --> 03:33.934
make the most sense?

03:33.934 --> 03:35.816
‐Aiko and Matteo haven't been
to space, either.

03:35.816 --> 03:37.217
That shouldn't be a basis
for whether ‐‐

03:37.217 --> 03:39.780
‐Understood, but like you said,

03:39.780 --> 03:42.703
Aiko's our engineer, and Matteo
keeps everyone healthy.

03:42.703 --> 03:46.026
In fact, both of their jobs are
directly related to survival.

03:46.026 --> 03:50.310
‐Remember, the focus of Crew Two
was supposed to be science.

03:50.310 --> 03:52.593
Now, I understand Crew One
was proof of concept.

03:52.593 --> 03:55.355
That falls on us now.
But we shouldn't abandon

03:55.355 --> 04:00.040
what this team
was originally designed for.

04:00.040 --> 04:02.963
Sadie has doctorates
in geology and biology,

04:02.963 --> 04:06.406
years doing core‐sample research
in Antarctica.

04:06.406 --> 04:09.810
There is no one better equipped.

04:11.692 --> 04:13.934
‐What do you think, Tom?

04:13.934 --> 04:18.058
‐I think we need
to discuss it further.

04:18.058 --> 04:20.621
‐So, are you not in alignment?
‐I ‐‐

04:20.621 --> 04:23.263
This was just an opportunity
to get your input.

04:25.786 --> 04:28.869
‐NASA would like to announce
this crew sooner than later.

04:28.869 --> 04:31.151
Give it the feeling
of inevitability,

04:31.151 --> 04:32.593
put faces to the mission.

04:32.593 --> 04:34.394
‐We ‐‐ We understand that.

04:34.394 --> 04:36.837
‐And is NASA good
with either choice?

04:36.837 --> 04:38.759
‐We defer to the commander.

04:38.759 --> 04:42.042
‐Okay, well, I'm sure Tom
will make the right decision.

04:42.042 --> 04:44.364
‐Thank you both.

04:44.364 --> 04:46.567
‐Thank you, Bob.

04:50.090 --> 04:52.613
‐This shake‐up is
disruptive enough.

04:52.613 --> 04:54.454
We can't devalue the science.

04:54.454 --> 04:57.978
It changes
the whole team dynamic.

04:57.978 --> 05:00.941
‐Look, I don't think
I'm gonna make it tonight.

05:00.941 --> 05:02.703
‐You have to.
It's her anniversary.

05:02.703 --> 05:04.745
‐Yeah, so they should have fun.

05:04.745 --> 05:06.346
Not have this hanging
over their head.

05:06.346 --> 05:07.588
‐It would be good for you
to spend some time

05:07.588 --> 05:09.149
with them off the clock.

05:09.149 --> 05:10.911
‐Yeah, but I'm the reason
somebody's gonna be cut.

05:10.911 --> 05:15.475
They don't need the grim reaper
at the party.

05:15.475 --> 05:18.639
‐You're leaning toward Sadie?

05:18.639 --> 05:20.440
That's why you don't want it
to influence you ‐‐

05:20.440 --> 05:22.122
seeing her celebrate her ‐‐
‐I don't want to be influenced

05:22.122 --> 05:25.325
by anything
until we've made a decision.

05:30.971 --> 05:32.332
‐About an hour ago.

05:32.332 --> 05:33.654
‐What are
the diagnostics saying?

05:33.654 --> 05:35.736
‐No response.
‐None?

05:35.736 --> 05:36.777
‐Look at this.

05:39.860 --> 05:41.982
‐Well, that can't be right.

05:41.982 --> 05:43.664
‐It has to be the software.

05:43.664 --> 05:45.946
‐Pull up the onboard cameras,
please.

05:51.071 --> 05:52.593
It doesn't look like
we have a leak.

05:52.593 --> 05:54.515
We'd see some kind of
atmospheric variance.

05:54.515 --> 05:56.757
If the LO‐‐

05:56.757 --> 05:58.478
Pull the cameras back up,
please.

05:58.478 --> 06:01.922
‐Did they crash?

06:01.922 --> 06:03.884
‐The onboard cameras
are not responding.

06:03.884 --> 06:06.687
We have visuals from the rest
of the hardware on the surface,

06:06.687 --> 06:09.690
but I'm more worried
about the sensor data.

06:09.690 --> 06:11.371
There's no atmospheric
temperature reading,

06:11.371 --> 06:16.016
and, uh, LOX levels
seem to be missing, too.

06:16.016 --> 06:18.699
‐And this all happened
after the software update?

06:18.699 --> 06:21.221
‐Yes.
‐How serious is this?

06:21.221 --> 06:24.224
‐Well, I can't say
until we re‐spin the EHA.

06:24.224 --> 06:25.906
‐I'll need a full rundown
for my report.

06:25.906 --> 06:28.428
The problem, probable causes,
next steps.

06:28.428 --> 06:30.430
‐We've had comms issues
with the MAV before.

06:30.430 --> 06:32.152
‐Isolated.
This looks systemic.

06:32.152 --> 06:34.034
‐Let's not jump
to any conclusions.

06:34.034 --> 06:36.637
This isn't a crisis yet.

06:36.637 --> 06:39.399
‐We don't know if our ascent
vehicle is making fuel.

06:39.399 --> 06:42.402
Even if it is, we don't know
if it's operational.

06:42.402 --> 06:43.884
Would that be
a correct assessment?

06:43.884 --> 06:46.887
‐You don't need to put this
in your report.

06:46.887 --> 06:49.970
Let's not get the folks
all riled up in DC.

06:53.814 --> 06:56.416
‐I'm gonna get back
to my people,

06:56.416 --> 06:58.579
start working on that rundown.

07:00.741 --> 07:03.223
[ Door opens ]

07:03.223 --> 07:04.825
[ Door closes ]

07:05.906 --> 07:08.308
‐Think about what
you're asking me to do.

07:08.308 --> 07:09.790
‐There's nothing wrong
with waiting

07:09.790 --> 07:11.271
until we have more information.

07:11.271 --> 07:13.554
‐My responsibility
is to the taxpayers.

07:13.554 --> 07:15.956
‐And I'm just asking that
we hold off

07:15.956 --> 07:19.319
until we know exactly what ‐‐
‐Stop.

07:19.319 --> 07:22.082
Please do not cross this line.

07:23.283 --> 07:25.125
‐There you go.

07:25.125 --> 07:28.809
Second round in five minutes!

07:28.809 --> 07:33.774
♪♪

07:33.774 --> 07:36.537
‐Okay, slow down.
Mom.

07:36.537 --> 07:39.620
That ‐‐ That doesn't go
with anything else on the menu.

07:39.620 --> 07:42.943
‐Thomas loves my shoyu.
‐Tom's not coming.

07:42.943 --> 07:46.066
‐Then I'll eat it.
Your tri‐tip's too salty.

07:46.066 --> 07:48.509
‐Your pork's too fatty.
Hey, kids, what did I say?

07:48.509 --> 07:51.311
Go clean up before dinner.
Okay, go, go!

07:51.311 --> 07:53.634
‐Are you sure we can't do
anything to help?

07:53.634 --> 07:56.236
‐What? No!
You two are the guests of honor.

07:58.799 --> 08:02.162
‐I need a serving spoon.
‐Oh, uh, you know what,

08:02.162 --> 08:03.764
there's one on the counter.

08:03.764 --> 08:06.607
‐Oh, okay. All right, thanks.
‐Try this.

08:06.607 --> 08:08.529
‐Oh, thanks.
‐This is my ‐‐ This is my move.

08:08.529 --> 08:09.970
‐Okay.
‐Let me try.

08:09.970 --> 08:11.331
‐This is how ‐‐
you know, when I get ‐‐

08:11.331 --> 08:13.654
‐Mmm! That needs more sugar.

08:13.654 --> 08:15.095
‐Don't question
my barbecue sauce.

08:15.095 --> 08:16.657
‐She's right.
It needs more.

08:16.657 --> 08:18.138
‐You, too?
‐Oh, I'm sorry.

08:18.138 --> 08:19.620
Did I bruise your fragile ego?

08:19.620 --> 08:21.101
‐Ohh!
‐Ohh!

08:21.101 --> 08:23.624
‐I like her style!
‐Yeah, she's a keeper.

08:23.624 --> 08:25.786
‐Hey, I‐I‐I can take
a little criticism.

08:25.786 --> 08:26.947
I'm man enough.

08:26.947 --> 08:29.670
♪♪

08:29.670 --> 08:32.673
[ Cicadas buzzing ]

08:41.922 --> 08:43.163
‐There it is.

08:46.927 --> 08:49.249
‐Wait, wait.
Hang on. Hang on.

08:49.249 --> 08:50.811
Okay.

08:50.811 --> 08:53.173
Got it?

08:53.173 --> 08:55.576
All right.
Okay, a little further up.

08:55.576 --> 08:57.017
Okay?
‐I got it.

08:57.017 --> 08:58.338
‐Got it?
‐Yeah.

08:58.338 --> 09:00.020
‐Okay.

09:08.829 --> 09:10.991
‐There's no way we're making
this rendezvous by 18:00.

09:10.991 --> 09:13.634
‐Well, we just have
to pick up the pace.

09:13.634 --> 09:16.917
‐Let me see.

09:16.917 --> 09:19.079
Uh, 18 kilometers.

09:19.079 --> 09:21.241
Straight shot.
More like 30 with this pond.

09:21.241 --> 09:22.563
‐We average three kilometers

09:22.563 --> 09:24.004
an hour, we should ‐‐
‐There's no way.

09:27.928 --> 09:31.772
We have to leave her.

09:31.772 --> 09:34.294
We already burned
35 minutes on this.

09:34.294 --> 09:35.696
It's time to make a decision.

09:35.696 --> 09:37.738
‐I don't want to leave
someone behind.

09:42.062 --> 09:45.746
‐Either you and me survive,
or no one does.

09:45.746 --> 09:48.949
I guarantee you the other team
is leaving Tom.

09:48.949 --> 09:51.512
‐I don't care what
the other team is doing.

09:54.715 --> 09:56.076
‐All right, well,
if you don't come with me,

09:56.076 --> 09:57.237
I'm gonna go on my own.

09:57.237 --> 10:02.042
♪♪

10:02.042 --> 10:03.403
‐Then go on your own.

10:03.403 --> 10:10.731
♪♪

10:10.731 --> 10:18.018
♪♪

10:18.018 --> 10:19.980
<i>Should I go with him?</i>

10:19.980 --> 10:23.263
<i>‐I can't weigh in.</i>

10:23.263 --> 10:25.425
‐Pause.

10:29.429 --> 10:31.431
‐Never even heard of it
before last year.

10:31.431 --> 10:33.433
‐It's, um ‐‐ it's a part of the,
uh...

10:33.433 --> 10:35.716
[ Indistinct conversations ]

10:35.716 --> 10:37.157
‐Yeah. Yeah, it was like ‐‐
‐Right?

10:37.157 --> 10:39.319
‐So, I don't know
the story of how you guys...

10:39.319 --> 10:41.081
Actually, you know what?
[ Glass clinking ]

10:41.081 --> 10:42.883
Guys, guys.

10:42.883 --> 10:45.966
Ollie's gonna tell us the story
of how he proposed. Right?

10:45.966 --> 10:47.487
‐Yes!
‐Aw!

10:47.487 --> 10:49.089
‐Don't we want to hear this?
‐It's a good one.

10:49.089 --> 10:50.450
‐Is it?
‐Pretty good.

10:50.450 --> 10:53.053
‐The comedy of errors
of my proposal.

10:53.053 --> 10:55.375
Um...

10:55.375 --> 10:58.659
So, I chose this spot at the
bottom of a beautiful garden

10:58.659 --> 11:01.902
and we're under a tree
and there's a love seat. And...

11:01.902 --> 11:05.305
‐Oh, how convenient.
‐This a proposal or a murder?

11:05.305 --> 11:08.028
‐Oh, my God!
[ Laughter ]

11:08.028 --> 11:11.311
‐We want answers
for that question, as well.

11:11.311 --> 11:12.472
‐I've got the ring
in my pocket...

11:12.472 --> 11:14.194
‐Okay.
‐...and my heart's going.

11:14.194 --> 11:17.437
And a bird shits on my head.

11:17.437 --> 11:18.519
‐Oh!
‐No!

11:18.519 --> 11:20.280
‐Yeah.

11:20.280 --> 11:24.845
‐So, there I am with this glob
of bird shit on my head.

11:24.845 --> 11:26.527
‐It was that big.

11:26.527 --> 11:29.169
‐And I refuse to acknowledge
its existence.

11:29.169 --> 11:30.370
‐What?
‐What?

11:30.370 --> 11:32.252
‐I mean,
I've been planning this.

11:32.252 --> 11:34.855
I'll be fucked if some pigeon's
incontinence is gonna ruin it.

11:34.855 --> 11:37.177
‐Oh, my God.
‐You don't say anything?

11:37.177 --> 11:39.099
‐Well, if he wasn't going to,
neither was I?

11:39.099 --> 11:41.341
‐I take ‐‐ I take her hand...
‐Oh!

11:41.341 --> 11:43.023
‐...very romantic‐like...

11:43.023 --> 11:46.587
‐What is...? Oh, wow!
‐Oh, my God!

11:46.587 --> 11:50.831
‐...and I say, "Listen to me"...

11:50.831 --> 11:52.873
‐Yes.
‐..."you stuck‐up"...

11:52.873 --> 11:54.114
‐No.

11:54.114 --> 11:58.158
‐..."brilliant
pain in my ass"...

11:58.158 --> 12:00.440
‐Brilliant's good.
‐What?

12:00.440 --> 12:02.963
‐..."you are going to marry me
one day."

12:07.327 --> 12:11.892
Three fucking years later,
persistence won the day, and...

12:11.892 --> 12:15.335
‐Here we are.
‐...alas, here we are.

12:15.335 --> 12:19.900
Thank you for joining us
on this our, um ‐‐

12:19.900 --> 12:21.582
What is it?
‐Really?

12:21.582 --> 12:22.863
‐Oh, boy.
‐Wow.

12:22.863 --> 12:24.945
‐Yeah.
‐Ooh, whoa.

12:24.945 --> 12:28.308
‐Eighth.
‐Ohh!

12:28.308 --> 12:33.313
‐He deserved that.
‐Wow. Thank you, Aiko and Todd.

12:33.313 --> 12:34.875
Thank you so much.
‐Yes, thank you.

12:34.875 --> 12:37.678
Cheers to this beautiful dinner.

12:37.678 --> 12:38.999
‐You're welcome!
‐Cheers!

12:38.999 --> 12:40.641
‐It's a treat!
‐It's time to say grace.

12:40.641 --> 12:42.563
‐Cheers.
‐Cheers.

12:42.563 --> 12:44.324
‐Cheers.
‐Mm‐hmm!

12:44.324 --> 12:47.127
‐It's time to say grace.

12:52.452 --> 12:55.175
‐We did that already, Mom.

12:55.175 --> 12:58.699
‐Well, we have to say grace
before we eat.

12:58.699 --> 13:02.382
‐We ate.
Um, the meal's over.

13:09.510 --> 13:13.393
Let's say grace in your bedroom?
Then you can go to sleep.

13:13.393 --> 13:14.915
Come on.

13:14.915 --> 13:17.357
‐Good night, everyone.
‐Good night.

13:17.357 --> 13:19.600
‐Night‐night.
‐Good night, Edith.

13:21.121 --> 13:23.003
‐Good night, Mom.

13:32.613 --> 13:41.982
♪♪

13:41.982 --> 13:44.625
‐Last one.

13:44.625 --> 13:46.306
‐Busy fucking shift, huh?

13:46.306 --> 13:49.550
‐No shit.
‐Hey, you coming out tonight?

13:49.550 --> 13:53.594
‐I don't know.
I just want to go home, shower.

13:53.594 --> 13:56.436
‐Stay dirty. Come out.

14:00.721 --> 14:03.524
‐It's called the Mars
Ascent Vehicle. The MAV.

14:03.524 --> 14:05.405
It's on the surface.

14:05.405 --> 14:08.128
‐It's already there?
‐It was sent ahead of time.

14:08.128 --> 14:09.970
To make its fuel
from the atmosphere.

14:09.970 --> 14:13.093
‐Well, technically, it turns CO2
into liquid oxygen.

14:13.093 --> 14:14.855
It takes about 10 months.

14:14.855 --> 14:21.421
‐After our 18 months is up,
we get inside, it takes off,

14:21.421 --> 14:23.263
and docks with the MTV,

14:23.263 --> 14:27.427
which is already in orbit,
and brings us back to Earth.

14:27.427 --> 14:29.469
‐So, if that's not working,
then there's

14:29.469 --> 14:30.911
no way for you to come ‐‐
‐Mnh‐mnh.

14:30.911 --> 14:32.713
‐Don't.
‐We're fucked. We're fucked.

14:32.713 --> 14:34.314
Marooned.
It's a one‐way ticket.

14:34.314 --> 14:36.196
‐Seriously. Seriously. Really?
‐It's true.

14:36.196 --> 14:38.278
‐You still want to, uh,
date an astronaut?

14:38.278 --> 14:39.560
You sure? You sure?

14:39.560 --> 14:41.121
‐Uh, ask me
after the second date.

14:41.121 --> 14:43.564
‐Ohh!
‐Ohh! Oh! Oh!

14:43.564 --> 14:45.806
Man got himself a second date!

14:45.806 --> 14:48.809
[ Indistinct conversations ]

14:48.809 --> 14:51.772
♪♪

14:51.772 --> 14:54.775
‐[ Breathing heavily ]

14:54.775 --> 15:02.342
♪♪

15:02.342 --> 15:09.910
♪♪

15:09.910 --> 15:11.552
‐Stop.

15:11.552 --> 15:13.554
Time's up.

15:13.554 --> 15:23.283
♪♪

15:23.283 --> 15:24.965
‐Thanks.

15:24.965 --> 15:30.130
♪♪

15:30.130 --> 15:35.295
♪♪

15:35.295 --> 15:38.378
‐You need to rest a bit?

15:38.378 --> 15:41.742
‐No.
‐Okay.

15:41.742 --> 15:42.983
Let's go.

15:42.983 --> 15:48.468
[ Cicadas buzzing ]

15:48.468 --> 15:52.673
‐50 klicks north of Adak,
New Year's Eve,

15:52.673 --> 15:54.955
capsized crab boat.

15:54.955 --> 15:58.038
The plan was to yank out
the survivors, get back to base,

15:58.038 --> 16:00.881
and be in the bar by the time
the ball drops on TV.

16:00.881 --> 16:03.203
But this fucking storm.

16:03.203 --> 16:05.085
Beaufort 10 gale.

16:07.247 --> 16:10.050
I'm flying low,
20 meters above the water,

16:10.050 --> 16:12.412
so I can find the raft.
It's dark.

16:12.412 --> 16:15.055
We've got our NVGs on.
We can barely see shit.

16:15.055 --> 16:17.297
Our co‐pilot finally
sees the target.

16:17.297 --> 16:19.139
Then alarms start going off.

16:19.139 --> 16:21.582
One of my engines flames out,

16:21.582 --> 16:25.986
and then this rogue wave slams
right into us, all right?

16:25.986 --> 16:29.590
Somehow, I get myself unstrapped
and out of there

16:29.590 --> 16:32.192
and I'm swimming like a madman.

16:32.192 --> 16:36.837
Then, boom, it's my chest,
and I can't move.

16:36.837 --> 16:39.920
And I'm like, "I'm gonna die."

16:39.920 --> 16:42.603
Then I did.

16:42.603 --> 16:44.845
‐You what?

16:44.845 --> 16:47.768
‐Died for seven minutes.

16:49.930 --> 16:51.932
‐Cold shock?
‐Yeah, the only thing

16:51.932 --> 16:54.374
that kept me from
going brain dead was the cold.

16:54.374 --> 16:56.296
Swimmer hauls me onto the raft.

16:56.296 --> 17:00.300
He breaks two ribs pumping till
the pistons start firing again.

17:00.300 --> 17:02.422
‐What happened to the others?

17:02.422 --> 17:05.145
‐Uh, mechanic made it.

17:05.145 --> 17:07.788
Co‐pilot didn't. Impact got him.

17:07.788 --> 17:11.351
Mike Vodanovich.

17:11.351 --> 17:13.634
Yeah, he was a good guy.

17:16.597 --> 17:20.320
Actually, he could be
a total asshole sometimes.

17:20.320 --> 17:22.042
He pulled this prank on me
once where we were...

17:22.042 --> 17:23.604
[ Twigs snap ]

17:35.776 --> 17:37.578
‐Any injuries?

17:37.578 --> 17:40.180
‐No.
‐You're five hours late.

17:40.180 --> 17:43.848
Go get some chow, get hydrated,
and stop by the medical tent.

17:43.848 --> 17:45.476
‐Yeah.

17:49.469 --> 17:50.871
‐She pushed herself
to the limit.

17:50.871 --> 17:53.393
‐That wasn't the point
of the exercise.

17:53.393 --> 17:55.115
‐She knows that.

17:55.115 --> 17:57.878
‐Well, she should have made
a different choice.

17:57.878 --> 18:04.324
♪♪

18:04.324 --> 18:07.127
‐You okay?
‐Yes.

18:09.249 --> 18:11.331
‐Yes!

18:11.331 --> 18:13.534
‐Hi.
‐Hi!

18:13.534 --> 18:17.017
You know what, I think
we can do much better than wine.

18:17.017 --> 18:19.820
‐Why? What do you have?

18:19.820 --> 18:21.742
‐Uh...

18:21.742 --> 18:23.704
Hmm?

18:23.704 --> 18:27.828
‐Hey, what is that?
‐Mezcal.

18:27.828 --> 18:31.431
I got these amazing
little copitas in Mexico City.

18:31.431 --> 18:35.676
You're supposed to use sliced
orange and chili, but fuck it.

18:35.676 --> 18:38.478
[ Cheering in distance ]

18:38.478 --> 18:40.360
‐Nice pour.

18:40.360 --> 18:42.162
‐[ Laughs ]

18:42.162 --> 18:44.284
‐Okay.
‐Cheers.

18:44.284 --> 18:46.246
[ Both laugh ]

18:50.931 --> 18:54.775
That is dangerous.

18:54.775 --> 18:55.976
‐[ Scottish accent ]
♪ When I wake up ♪

18:55.976 --> 18:58.498
♪ Well, I know I'm gonna be ♪

18:58.498 --> 19:01.141
♪ I'm gonna be the man
who wakes up next to you ♪

19:01.141 --> 19:02.222
‐Aw!

19:02.222 --> 19:04.024
‐♪ When I go out ♪

19:04.024 --> 19:05.826
♪ Yeah, I know I'm gonna be ♪

19:05.826 --> 19:09.349
♪ I'm gonna be the man
who goes along with you ♪

19:09.349 --> 19:10.591
‐Ollie!
‐And if I get drunk ♪

19:10.591 --> 19:11.792
‐Yes!
‐Yes!

19:11.792 --> 19:13.594
‐♪ Well, I know I'm gonna be ♪

19:13.594 --> 19:16.436
♪ I'm gonna be the man
who gets drunk next to you ♪

19:16.436 --> 19:18.398
♪ And if I haver up ♪

19:18.398 --> 19:20.160
♪ Yeah, I know I'm gonna be ♪

19:20.160 --> 19:24.044
♪ I'm gonna be the man
who's havering to you ♪

19:24.044 --> 19:28.088
♪ But I would walk 500 miles ♪

19:28.088 --> 19:31.652
♪ And I would walk 500 more ♪

19:31.652 --> 19:35.936
♪ Just be the man
who walks 1,000 miles ♪

19:35.936 --> 19:38.699
♪ To fall down at your door ♪

19:38.699 --> 19:40.941
♪ When I come home ♪
‐♪ When I come home ♪

19:40.941 --> 19:42.743
‐♪ Well, I know I'm gonna be ♪

19:42.743 --> 19:45.866
♪ I'm gonna be the man
who comes back home to you ♪

19:45.866 --> 19:47.788
‐♪ When I grow old ♪
‐♪ When I grow old ♪

19:47.788 --> 19:49.429
‐♪ Well, I know I'm gonna be ♪

19:49.429 --> 19:53.634
♪ I'm gonna be the man
who grows old next to you ♪

19:53.634 --> 19:57.237
♪ And I would walk 500 miles ♪

19:57.237 --> 20:00.480
♪ And I would walk 500 more ♪

20:00.480 --> 20:03.483
[ Jazz music playing ]

20:03.483 --> 20:06.486
[ Cheering ]

20:06.486 --> 20:13.293
♪♪

20:13.293 --> 20:20.100
♪♪

20:20.100 --> 20:26.907
♪♪

20:26.907 --> 20:28.589
‐Hey, hold my beer?

20:28.589 --> 20:36.276
♪♪

20:36.276 --> 20:43.924
♪♪

20:43.924 --> 20:51.612
♪♪

20:51.612 --> 20:54.535
‐I think I'm gonna head home.
You want to share a car?

20:55.776 --> 20:57.778
‐No, I'm good.

20:57.778 --> 21:00.140
‐It's late.
Let's ‐‐ Let's go.

21:00.140 --> 21:02.663
‐I'll see you tomorrow.

21:02.663 --> 21:11.672
♪♪

21:11.672 --> 21:20.641
♪♪

21:20.641 --> 21:29.650
♪♪

21:35.455 --> 21:37.217
‐...cannot.

21:37.217 --> 21:38.579
Oh.

21:38.579 --> 21:40.861
Wow!

21:40.861 --> 21:42.302
‐Come on in.

21:42.302 --> 21:46.466
‐[ Speaks indistinctly ]

21:46.466 --> 21:48.709
‐Wow.

21:48.709 --> 21:51.111
‐I love it!

21:51.111 --> 21:53.193
Mm, the smell of it!

21:59.920 --> 22:01.481
‐This one.

22:01.481 --> 22:03.684
‐Yes!

22:09.449 --> 22:11.051
‐Whoa.

22:11.051 --> 22:14.054
[ Pop‐rock music playing ]

22:14.054 --> 22:23.664
♪♪

22:23.664 --> 22:33.233
♪♪

22:33.233 --> 22:35.676
‐Your turn.

22:35.676 --> 22:44.765
♪♪

22:44.765 --> 22:53.854
♪♪

22:53.854 --> 22:56.937
‐Poor, little horndogs.

22:56.937 --> 23:02.262
♪♪

23:02.262 --> 23:07.908
13 years crawling around as
maggots all for this one moment,

23:07.908 --> 23:09.870
this urge,

23:09.870 --> 23:12.432
this undeniable need
to crawl out of the dirt

23:12.432 --> 23:14.675
and bang their brains out.

23:14.675 --> 23:17.397
And then, poof. Dead.

23:17.397 --> 23:20.961
We fuck.

23:20.961 --> 23:22.763
We die.

23:22.763 --> 23:25.165
We breathe.

23:25.165 --> 23:28.529
We die.

23:28.529 --> 23:32.653
We know we're going back
to the mud.

23:32.653 --> 23:37.297
But still, we live.

23:37.297 --> 23:44.264
♪♪

23:44.264 --> 23:51.231
♪♪

23:51.231 --> 23:58.158
♪♪

23:58.158 --> 24:05.125
♪♪

24:05.125 --> 24:12.092
♪♪

24:12.092 --> 24:13.934
‐Sorry.

24:13.934 --> 24:17.177
‐No. I‐I just ‐‐

24:17.177 --> 24:19.099
‐It's ‐‐ It's cool.
It's cool.

24:19.099 --> 24:23.223
♪♪

24:23.223 --> 24:26.867
‐We're not supposed to
for the first year.

24:26.867 --> 24:32.392
I mean, a year's almost up,
but still...

24:32.392 --> 24:34.555
‐You're not supposed to what?

24:34.555 --> 24:38.038
‐Any relationships.

24:38.038 --> 24:39.119
My meetings.

24:39.119 --> 24:41.922
♪♪

24:41.922 --> 24:44.965
‐Oh, shit. I forgot.

24:44.965 --> 24:47.287
Oh, sorry. I ‐‐
‐No, no, no, no, no, no, no.

24:47.287 --> 24:49.249
No, you're fine.

24:49.249 --> 24:53.774
‐Yeah?
‐Go for it.

24:53.774 --> 25:03.423
♪♪

25:03.423 --> 25:07.948
‐So, we were just kind of
messing around, right?

25:07.948 --> 25:12.553
Nothing serious,
like a, uh, relationship?

25:12.553 --> 25:14.635
♪♪

25:14.635 --> 25:19.560
[ Both laugh ]

25:19.560 --> 25:21.281
You wouldn't want to be with me,
anyways.

25:21.281 --> 25:24.645
I mean, I snore.
I've got holes in my underwear.

25:24.645 --> 25:28.088
I piss with the door open.

25:28.088 --> 25:30.130
I mean, the sex is good.

25:30.130 --> 25:33.333
So I've been told.

25:33.333 --> 25:36.777
And I can cook.

25:36.777 --> 25:39.700
‐You can dance.
‐I can dance.

25:39.700 --> 25:41.982
I can cook
and dance simultaneously

25:41.982 --> 25:44.344
<i>and</i> say
the Pledge of Allegiance.

25:44.344 --> 25:46.386
‐[ Laughs ]

25:46.386 --> 25:54.154
♪♪

25:54.154 --> 26:01.962
♪♪

26:01.962 --> 26:09.730
♪♪

26:09.730 --> 26:12.372
‐I have got an early day.

26:12.372 --> 26:14.494
♪♪

26:14.494 --> 26:15.976
‐The music.

26:15.976 --> 26:18.298
♪♪

26:18.298 --> 26:19.339
[ Music stops ]

26:19.339 --> 26:22.382
‐This the astronaut?

26:22.382 --> 26:24.024
I've never touched
a real live astronaut before.

26:24.024 --> 26:25.305
‐You really don't want
to come near me.

26:25.305 --> 26:26.987
‐Let's go. Let's go.
Come on. Guys.

26:26.987 --> 26:28.829
Go home.

26:36.877 --> 26:38.879
‐Bye.
‐Bye.

26:43.403 --> 26:46.046
‐This guy?
‐His name is Finn.

26:46.046 --> 26:47.808
‐I don't give a damn
what his name is.

26:47.808 --> 26:50.531
He had weed, Denise.

26:50.531 --> 26:52.452
‐I didn't smoke any.

26:52.452 --> 26:55.015
Oh, believe what you want.

26:55.015 --> 26:56.376
‐Denise.
‐I didn't do anything wrong.

26:56.376 --> 26:58.098
‐Why do you put yourself
at risk like this?

26:58.098 --> 26:59.540
You got booze everywhere, drugs.

26:59.540 --> 27:01.742
‐I work in a fucking bar, Dad.

27:01.742 --> 27:03.744
‐But you brought it here,
in our house.

27:03.744 --> 27:05.906
‐What do you want me to do,
not go out? Not have friends?

27:05.906 --> 27:07.788
‐I want you to think.

27:12.913 --> 27:16.877
‐"I want you to think."

27:16.877 --> 27:18.559
That's exactly
what you used to say to mom.

27:18.559 --> 27:20.320
‐We're talking about you,
not her.

27:20.320 --> 27:22.002
‐Do you have any idea
how that made her feel

27:22.002 --> 27:24.565
when you said that?!

27:24.565 --> 27:26.206
You know, every time
I bring her up, you run.

27:26.206 --> 27:27.888
‐I'm not running.

27:27.888 --> 27:29.970
‐No, you're just pretending
like it didn't happen.

27:29.970 --> 27:32.012
‐You got to let it go.

27:32.012 --> 27:34.254
You can't let her bring us down,
too.

27:52.953 --> 27:55.115
‐Dad.

28:05.165 --> 28:06.687
Do you remember
what she used to say

28:06.687 --> 28:09.089
to make us smile,
instead of "cheese"?

28:16.537 --> 28:20.581
‐One...two...three...

28:20.581 --> 28:22.823
‐"Say, 'motherfucker.'"

28:36.637 --> 28:39.319
‐When was this?

28:39.319 --> 28:41.762
‐That was the day you got
back from the moon.

28:41.762 --> 28:43.964
‐The day of the parade?
‐Yeah. Yeah.

28:43.964 --> 28:46.246
Everyone wanted to take selfies
with you,

28:46.246 --> 28:49.449
so I thought
we should get our own.

28:51.171 --> 28:54.174
‐I don't want to fight.

28:54.174 --> 28:55.536
‐Me, either.

28:58.018 --> 29:00.340
‐I trust you ‐‐
I‐I want to trust you.

29:00.340 --> 29:02.503
I‐I do trust you.

29:05.065 --> 29:08.188
‐Maybe you should come
to one of my meetings?

29:08.188 --> 29:10.070
See for yourself.

29:10.070 --> 29:12.753
‐Would they allow that?
‐Yeah, anyone can come.

29:15.435 --> 29:17.638
‐I'd like that.

29:17.638 --> 29:21.602
‐Yeah.

29:21.602 --> 29:23.524
Okay.

29:23.524 --> 29:26.567
‐Get yourself some sleep.

29:26.567 --> 29:27.568
‐You, too.

29:53.954 --> 29:55.315
‐Shouldn't have scheduled this

29:55.315 --> 29:58.158
the day after we all
drank like fishes.

29:59.399 --> 30:01.962
Okay.

30:09.329 --> 30:11.532
Sleep?
‐Normal.

30:11.532 --> 30:13.734
‐Appetite?
‐Good.

30:13.734 --> 30:15.936
‐How are your dreams?

30:15.936 --> 30:18.659
‐You never asked me
about my dreams before.

30:18.659 --> 30:20.701
‐I'm asking now.

30:20.701 --> 30:23.223
‐I don't dream.

30:23.223 --> 30:27.107
‐Everyone does.
‐Not me.

30:27.107 --> 30:29.710
‐So, you're saying
you don't remember them.

30:31.752 --> 30:37.357
♪♪

30:37.357 --> 30:43.003
♪♪

30:43.003 --> 30:46.366
‐What were you thinking
climbing that high?

30:46.366 --> 30:50.531
‐I want to go to space.

30:50.531 --> 30:53.734
Do you think that's stupid?

30:53.734 --> 30:56.937
‐Might be better ways to prepare
than climbing fences

30:56.937 --> 30:58.699
and busting your arm.

31:03.383 --> 31:06.947
No. I don't think
it's stupid at all.

31:09.670 --> 31:11.111
‐You are wrong, Tom.
‐Let me finish.

31:11.111 --> 31:12.513
‐I'm telling you you are wrong.

31:12.513 --> 31:15.115
‐She does not have
what it takes.

31:15.115 --> 31:18.599
‐Yes, she does.
I'm certain of it.

31:18.599 --> 31:21.201
Listen, Nick ‐‐ He'll be fine.

31:21.201 --> 31:22.763
He'll take it like a pro.

31:22.763 --> 31:24.725
I'll tell him it was
my recommendation.

31:24.725 --> 31:27.007
He will respect that,
and it insulates you.

31:27.007 --> 31:30.370
‐I watched the survival training
again last night.

31:30.370 --> 31:32.252
‐She learned the lesson.
‐She had the wrong instinct.

31:32.252 --> 31:33.814
‐That is what
the training is for.

31:33.814 --> 31:35.736
‐You cannot teach instinct.

31:35.736 --> 31:39.740
I need people who are gonna do
the hard thing. That's all.

31:39.740 --> 31:41.221
‐Is this still a discussion?

31:41.221 --> 31:43.343
‐We can keep discussing it
if you want to.

31:43.343 --> 31:44.545
‐Yeah, but you made
up your mind.

31:44.545 --> 31:47.427
‐I have.

31:47.427 --> 31:50.911
Is that gonna be a problem?

31:50.911 --> 31:52.633
Because we've got
a long road ahead.

31:52.633 --> 31:54.314
‐No.
No problem at all.

31:54.314 --> 31:57.477
‐All right, then I'll get
the approval from Laz and Bob,

31:57.477 --> 31:59.279
and we'll tell the crew
tomorrow.

32:05.165 --> 32:06.687
[ Clears throat ]

32:14.094 --> 32:17.337
‐You're home early.
‐Yeah, just physicals today.

32:17.337 --> 32:20.541
‐Hey.
‐Oh. Sorry.

32:20.541 --> 32:22.943
‐Grab some paper.

32:22.943 --> 32:24.825
‐I thought you were out
in the Irish Channel.

32:24.825 --> 32:26.587
‐Final coat on the walls.

32:26.587 --> 32:28.509
I don't need
to literally watch paint dry.

32:28.509 --> 32:31.191
No, no, the 320 grit.

32:31.191 --> 32:32.673
It's gonna be a gorgeous house.

32:32.673 --> 32:35.075
Just put in these, uh,
asymmetric skylights.

32:35.075 --> 32:37.277
I'll take you by this weekend.

32:43.043 --> 32:45.886
Hey. Lighter. Lighter.
This is the finish.

32:54.094 --> 32:57.257
♪♪

32:57.257 --> 32:59.980
‐What's your hesitation?

32:59.980 --> 33:03.223
‐The facilities are phenomenal.

33:03.223 --> 33:05.065
The chance to do
this sort of science...

33:05.065 --> 33:08.869
‐But...
‐I have to speak to my husband.

33:08.869 --> 33:12.432
It's a big life change for him,
for both of us to move here.

33:12.432 --> 33:14.234
He's on tenure track
at Cambridge.

33:14.234 --> 33:17.397
‐Tell him we've had
2,000 scientists apply.

33:17.397 --> 33:19.840
I've personally met over 50.

33:19.840 --> 33:20.921
I want you.

33:23.844 --> 33:25.726
‐When I submitted
my application,

33:25.726 --> 33:28.288
I don't even know why I did it.

33:28.288 --> 33:30.571
It's not like I've always
wanted to be an astronaut.

33:30.571 --> 33:33.213
‐Let me ask you a question.
Straight up.

33:33.213 --> 33:36.216
Are you the best at what you do?

33:36.216 --> 33:38.378
I think you are.

33:38.378 --> 33:41.742
And you know you are.
That's why you applied.

33:41.742 --> 33:43.383
But if you think
there's someone better,

33:43.383 --> 33:45.746
please tell me because
I should be speaking to them

33:45.746 --> 33:47.187
instead of you.

33:47.187 --> 33:51.271
♪♪

33:51.271 --> 33:53.273
‐No.
There's no one better.

33:53.273 --> 33:57.638
‐You could be the person
that discovers life on Mars.

33:57.638 --> 34:00.440
Does your husband
understand that?

34:00.440 --> 34:04.364
More importantly,
do you understand that?

34:04.364 --> 34:06.326
‐I'd be losing years of work

34:06.326 --> 34:07.808
if I don't
make it through training.

34:07.808 --> 34:11.211
‐You will.
‐You can't promise that.

34:11.211 --> 34:13.133
‐Trust me on this.

34:13.133 --> 34:16.817
You've got that thing.

34:16.817 --> 34:20.981
You'll make it.

34:20.981 --> 34:22.903
I promise you.

34:54.535 --> 34:58.659
‐You here?
Or someplace else?

34:58.659 --> 35:03.624
‐When is the bedroom
gonna get finished?

35:03.624 --> 35:05.986
I've had enough
of this air mattress.

35:09.389 --> 35:11.311
‐Want to talk about it?

35:13.954 --> 35:16.957
‐Decisions get made.

35:16.957 --> 35:18.599
Fine.

35:18.599 --> 35:20.721
And some are wrong.

35:20.721 --> 35:22.963
Fine.

35:22.963 --> 35:25.485
Can I live with this one?

35:25.485 --> 35:28.048
Yes.

35:28.048 --> 35:29.570
But I always make it work.

35:29.570 --> 35:32.332
My ‐‐
My whole ‐‐ My whole career.

35:32.332 --> 35:36.897
And I‐I just feel like
at this point,

35:36.897 --> 35:40.260
enough already!

35:40.260 --> 35:41.902
I mean...

35:41.902 --> 35:45.065
Listen to me.
I know what I'm talking about.

35:45.065 --> 35:47.708
I‐I've been given this command
for a reason.

35:47.708 --> 35:50.430
I've earned it.
I've excelled at it. And I...

35:52.753 --> 35:57.357
And here we are again!

35:57.357 --> 36:00.040
And I just feel...

36:00.040 --> 36:02.402
‐Maybe you need to talk to Laz.

36:02.402 --> 36:05.606
‐Mm, chain of command.

36:05.606 --> 36:07.447
‐Screw chain of command.
‐No, that ‐‐ that ‐‐

36:07.447 --> 36:08.849
that chain of command
got me where I am.

36:08.849 --> 36:10.931
‐And your silence
is being rewarded.

36:14.414 --> 36:17.538
You are spending 2 1/2 years
with this guy.

36:17.538 --> 36:20.821
‐I'll get through this.

36:20.821 --> 36:23.223
I just need to recalibrate.

36:25.786 --> 36:30.711
‐It's ‐‐ Uh, you know, it's like
that song I sang at summer camp.

36:30.711 --> 36:32.432
♪ And the cat came back ♪

36:32.432 --> 36:34.875
♪ The very next day ♪

36:34.875 --> 36:37.798
And she's all like,
"Feed me. Meow!"

36:37.798 --> 36:39.720
But this bitch just barks back.

36:39.720 --> 36:42.402
She runs off.

36:42.402 --> 36:46.807
So, you know,
as long as I got some dog in me,

36:46.807 --> 36:50.971
one day, one bark at a time.

36:50.971 --> 36:53.654
Yeah.
Uh, so anyway, thanks, guys.

36:53.654 --> 36:56.216
‐Thanks, Myk.
‐Thanks, Myk.

36:56.216 --> 37:00.500
‐I'm Denise.
Dopeless hope fiend.

37:00.500 --> 37:03.904
[ Laughter ]
‐Hi, Denise.

37:03.904 --> 37:07.107
‐Uh, I've been good, I guess.

37:07.107 --> 37:09.389
I kept a job for more
than three months.

37:09.389 --> 37:11.672
That is a big one for me.

37:11.672 --> 37:14.675
Myk here makes sure
I don't fuck up too bad.

37:14.675 --> 37:19.880
Um, the painting's
been going okay.

37:19.880 --> 37:22.683
I hate thinking about it like
it's some sort of therapy

37:22.683 --> 37:27.688
or something,
but it is, I guess.

